	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>EU aid to the fishing sectors of tsunami-affected countries</h1>

			
			<h4>
												31 January 2005
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p> The situation in countries affected by the December 26th 2004 tsunami was discussed at the January 24th 2005 meeting of the Agriculture and Fisheries Council. The fisheries sectors (mainly small-scale) were the hardest hit in the tsunami-affected ACP countries of Kenya, Madagascar, Somalia and the Seychelles.</p><p> In Somalia the tsunami caused extensive damage along 600 kilometres of the coastline, with between 100 and 300 people killed, and thousands of others affected. It struck at the height of the fishing season, which draws people from across Somalia, and from as far away as Tanzania and Zanzibar. The Seychelles suffered severe flooding and widespread damage to roads and fishing infrastructure. A preliminary assessment puts damage to the latter at around $6.8 million.</p><p> EU Fisheries Commissioner Joe Borg spoke of the emergency measures being proposed by the Commission and said that it was preparing a review of possible financial support and 'flanking measures'. These include both aid programmes to rehabilitate the fisheries sectors and the transfer of decommissioned vessels of up to 12 metres in length. It was important, he said, to guarantee coordination under the aegis of the UN through the FAO. The principles that would guide EU actions in this domain included the adequacy of the response to needs, sustainability, adaptability and respect for traditional local fishing patterns.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
<a href="http://www.europa.eu.int/comm/fisheries/news_corner/press/inf05_04_en.htm" target="_self">EC press release on the outcome of the Agriculture and Fisheries Council...</a> </p><p>
<a href="http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/IRIN/126091cec94e2944fef642eebcf12fbb.htm" target="_self">Press article on the post-tsunami situation in Somalia</a> </p><p>
<a href="http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/IRIN/e74dce627695f8cc38d04992d3bd8c80.htm" target="_self">Press article on the post-tsunami economic situation in the Seychelles</a> </p><p>

<a href="http://www2.europarl.eu.int/omk/sipade2?PUBREF=-//EP//TEXT+PRESS+NR-20050126-1+0+DOC+XML+V0//EN&amp;L=EN&amp;LEVEL=2&amp;NAV=X&amp;LSTDOC=N#SECTION2" target="_self">Report to the European Parliament on January 25th 2005</a> <br />
 I 
<a href="http://www.icsf.net/jsp/english/externalnews/newsDetails.jsp?id=18396" target="_self">CSF article 'Tsunami aid and EU vessel transfers: a political gesture or...</a> <br /> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> The decision to offer decommissioned fishing vessels to tsunami-affected countries has provoked controversy. On the one hand it has opened up the possibility for subsidising vessel transfers to some ACP countries. On the other it is felt that transferring vessels from the EU would disrupt local efforts, and detract from the development of sustainable fishing policies in the affected countries.</p><p> Commissioner Borg justified his decision on the basis that it would be unacceptable to refuse a request to transfer vessels to satisfy a need while continuing to pay for their destruction. In fact, some decommissioned vessel transfers have already taken place using alternative funding sources. However, the FAO has noted that 'it is important to precisely specify the design of boats, gear etc. as the local designs have been developed over time to be economically and technically sustainable. However good the intentions may be to send boats and gear to the affected countries, they may end up unused on the beaches if they are not adapted to the local environment'.</p><p> The EC is proposing that the FAO provide an objective evaluation of the local needs in terms of gear and vessels. Should this evaluation show that such a transfer represented an adequate response to meeting part of the needs, and that adequate vessels were available, the legal obstacles would have been cleared, and boat transfer could be eligible for support. But despite conditions for vessel transfers being set under the previous FIFG (financial instrument for fisheries guidance) these were not fully observed in practice. There is therefore cause for concern that pressure from EU member states rather than real local needs will provide the impetus for vessel transfers.</p><p> The proposal for the FAO to provide an objective needs assessment and resource evaluation also raises the question: should the FAO be involved in evaluating the needs of ACP countries in general prior to their signing of an FPA?</p>
		</div>
		
